There are 4 things I've experienced in relationships that make me want to throw in my 2 cents:
1. I have been emotionally abused in a relationship
2. I have been sexually abused in a relationship
3. I have been lied to/cheated on in relationships
4. I have now found healthy love with someone I'm marrying next month (praise God for pre-marital counseling)

You can heal if you are willing to work at it but you get a lot of messages that tend to encourage you to stay in your pain. So many people in the comments calling Loni and Adrienne insensitive don't realize that what abused people need is the strength and the truth which is that you CAN absolutely move forward and enjoy good things. Unfortunately, we are encouraged to leave our healing in the hands of how many people validate us and hear our story and cosign how we feel. People think it's nice to empathize and then just leave abused people to figure it out but the longer my friends and I sat in misery about our situation and how sad it was that "he lied" and "he hurt me" etc, the slower our growth and freedom process was. As long as someone cosigns your decision to dwell on the issue, you will not move forward. You have to choose health. It's not just given to you by time which means that healing can come as quickly as we let it. I would be remiss if I didn't add that the strength of Jesus Christ can lift you up out of anything. Change your language and change your perception. No one else has to agree with you for you to have been abused and no one else has to give you permission to rebuild. The encouragement is nice but healing only comes when YOU believe it.
